  "stage": {
    "id": "stage_2_transformer",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "Stage 2: The Transformer Internals",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "scaled_dot_product",
        "title": "Scaled Dot-Product Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Q/K/V matrices\n- scaling by √dₖ\n\nVaswani et al. (2017) compute Attention(Q,K,V)=softmax(QKᵀ/√dₖ)V. The √dₖ scaling keeps gradients healthy when the key dimension is large.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "multi_head_attention",
        "title": "Multi-Head Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- parallel heads\n- subspace diversity\n\nWith h=8 heads and dₖ=64, the model jointly attends to information from different representation subspaces — like reading a sentence for grammar, sentiment, and coreference all at once.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "positional_encoding",
        "title": "Positional Encoding",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- sin/cos frequencies\n- position-invariant attention\n\nPure attention treats inputs as a set, not a sequence. Vaswani et al. inject sinusoidal PE(pos,2i)=sin(pos/10000^(2i/d)) so the model knows token positions without recurrence.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "ffn",
        "title": "Position-wise Feed-Forward Network",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- per-position processing\n- dff=2048\n\nEach Transformer layer adds a two-layer FFN (dff=2048) applied identically and independently at every position — it stores per-token 'knowledge' while attention handles mixing.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "encoder_decoder",
        "title": "The Full Transformer",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- layer stacking\n- masked self-attention in decoder\n\nN=6 encoder layers process the input; N=6 decoder layers generate output autoregressively with masked self-attention to ensure predictions depend only on past tokens.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "What is the purpose of masking in the decoder's self-attention? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "To save memory",
        "To prevent the decoder from attending to future (not-yet-generated) tokens",
        "To ignore padding tokens"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "To prevent the decoder from attending to future (not-yet-generated) tokens",
      "position": {
        "x": 18,
        "y": 7
      }
    },
